markable development sustainable amid a century of political and cultural turmoil.The modern Zionist vision began as a quest to redeem a land that bore the cumulative effects of two thousand years of foreign domination and neglect. Since then, Israel has suffered from its success. A tenfold increase in population and standard of living has polluted the air. The deserts have bloomed but groundwater has become contaminated. Urban sprawl threatens to pave over much of the country's breathtaking landscape. Yet there is hope. Tal's account considers the ecological and tactical lessons that emerge from dozens of cases of environmental mishaps, from habitat loss to river reclamation. Pollution in a Promised Land argues that the priorities and strategies of Israeli environmental advocates must address issues beyond traditional green agendas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmental policyzIsrael. 0aEnvironmental protectionzIsrael. 0aPollutionzIsrael. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aair pollution.  aconservation.  acontaminated groundwater.  acultural study.  aearth sciences.  aecologists.  aenvironment sustainability.  aenvironmental activists.  aenvironmental advocates.  aenvironmental history.  aenvironmentalism.  aenvironmentalists.  aglobal issues.  ahabitat loss.  ahistorians.  aisrael.  ajudaism.  anonfiction.  apolitical activists.  apolitical issues.  apollution.  apopulation growth.  aregional history.  ariver reclamation.  atextbooks.  aurban sprawl.  azionists.1 aTal, Alon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023428440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093